Abstract
The Naive Bayesian algorithm for classication has been a staple in machine learning for
decades. Simple and ecient, the algorithm makes unrealistic independence assumptions
about the data; yet it performs very well, often nearly matching the performance of far
more complex modern algorithms. Only recently have researchers understood the theoret-
ical reasons for this unreasonably good performance. In 2004, Professor Harry Zhang of
the University of New Brunswick articulated the notion of a dependence-derivative factor,
which more denes precisely how much Naive Bayes is harmed by certain violations of
its independence assumption. In this project, I present a way to use Zhangs dependence
derivatives to create classiers similar to Naive Bayes, but with a network struture more
resilient of these violations.

Introduction
1.1 Classication
Classication is the familiar problem of examining something and deciding what it is. A
typical classication problem might involve being given a description of an object say a
piece of fruit and being asked to determine what type of fruit is being described. While
humans are able to classify objects intuitively and without much thought, developing al-
gorithms to enable machine classication is an ongoing problem in the eld of machine
learning, where classication is the dominant problem in the subeld of supervised learn-
ing.
Formally, a classier is a function f that maps an example E to a class c. An example
is usually represented as an ordered n-tuple of attributes (x
1
, x
2
, ..., x
n
). Typically, we
create a classier according to an algorithm, which examines a number of examples and
creates a classier function based on the data. In most cases, the classiers produced by
a given algorithm running on the same data will be equivalent, meaning that for identical
inputs, they will give identical outputs; because of this, it is common to refer to a classier
function and the algorithm that created it interchangeably.
1. INTRODUCTION 7
When managed well, classiers can quickly and quietly reduce the number of inconse-
quential decisions in our lives. Probably the most well-known example of a classier is an
email spam lter, which simply determines if an incoming email matches the known prole
of an unwanted advertisement. Spam lters are an illustrative example of the development
of classication technology; though it took a long time for spam lters to consistently get
it right, modern algorithms work so well that it is easy to forget that they are there.
Classiers can also have far more dramatic applications, however, than just sorting email.
The diagnosis of disease can be treated as a classication problem, as can the assignment
of a credit score.
Classication can be broken into two separate arenas: binary classication and multi-
class classication. In a binary classication problem, the classier attempts to distinguish
between only two classes; this reduction in complexity typically makes it much easier to
articulate the intuition behind how a classication algorithm works. For the most part, we
will discuss classiers as if they are binary distinguishing only between a positive class
(+), and a negative class (). Most of the ideas presented can be quickly generalized to
the multiple-class case. If the generalization is non-obvious, we may comment on how it
works out.

1.2 Bayesian Classiers
In this project, we focus on Bayesian classiers, which are named after their reliance
on Bayes Rule. Before we enter the discussion, however, we have to deal with a slightly
aggravating problem of terminology in this eld. We are about to enter a discussion of
the probabilities of various terms, some of which are single values or the intersection of
single values from a continuous range. Strictly speaking, the probability of such terms
is 0 what we actually mean is the value of a probability density function (for continuous
variables) or probability mass function (for discrete variables) at a specic point. However,
in the eight or so papers and two textbooks we examined that discussed Bayesian classiers,
all of them used the word probability to describe terms like those above. Some even did
so while using a little p which signies a density function in their notation. In an eort
be both expedient and conscious of the terminology, we are going to consciously accept
this convention. We will continue to speak of probabilities, but will use a small p instead
of a big P to remind both ourselves and the reader that in most cases these are in truth
density functions.

1.3 Naive Bayes
Notice that the complications in the full Bayesian classier arise from potential de-
pendencies among the attributes of the example. The probability computations can be
dramatically simplied by assuming that these dependencies do not exist that is, by
assuming that the attributes are independent of each other. The classier making this
assumption is referred to as the Naive Bayesian classier; the name comes from the
classier naively assuming that the attributes are not conspiring together behind its back.
Denition 1.3.1. The Naive Bayesian classier f
nb

p(c|E) yields and assume p(c) is known or easily accessed. The remaining term, p(E|c) is

Each of the terms of this product is easily computed; indeed, the entire algorithm is
easy to implement and much faster both than other Bayesian algorithms and non-Bayesian
classication algorithms: since it requires only one loop over the training data, a well-
written Naive Bayes classier takes O(dn) time to construct and O(1) time to evaluate
a single example, where d is the number of examples in the training data, and n is the
number of attributes.
Naive Bayes is a powerful classication algorithm that comes close to matching the per-
formance of far more complicated modern algorithms in empirical tests [3]. At rst glance,
this performance is somewhat puzzling, as the algorithms assumption of independence
among attributes is rarely realistic. Simple tests on highly dependent data-sets reveal that
the presence of dependence alone is not necessarily a problem for Naive Bayes. So while the
independence of attributes is a sucient condition for good performance for Naive Bayes,
it is not a necessary condition. Explaining Naive Bayes performance, and characterizing
specic conditions under which it performs well nding the minimal necessary condition
on the data has been an on-and-o problem in machine learning theory for some time.
1.4 Bayesian Classiers as Graphs
So far I have presented a view of classiers that mostly engages with the mathematical
underpinnings of what a Bayesian classier does. In practice, however, it is very common
for people to adapt the basics of what we have already discussed to create classiers
designed to deal with a specic problem. The easiest way to describe the way such classiers
work is by examining the topology of the graphs they dene.
1. INTRODUCTION 17
Denition 1.4.1. A Bayesian graph or Bayesian network is a graph representing
the model used by the classier to examine an example. It obeys the following two rules:
1. It is an acyclic digraph, usually with multiple sources and exactly one sink. This
sink represents the probability that an example is of a given class.
2. Each vertex represents the probability of some event occurring; edges indicate that
one event is dependent on another. If an edge goes from vertex A to vertex B, this
indicates that the probability of B is aected by the probability of A.
Multiple algorithms for constructing Bayesian networks exist, and they are not limited
to classication problems. The algorithm we will use is simple: we simply place down
one vertex for each attribute and one for the class value. We create one edge connecting
each attribute vertex to the class value, and one edge connecting each vertex to all other
vertices that are not independent of it. This is a bare-bones Bayesian network more
complicated networks have layers of vertices between the source vertices (the attributes)
and the sink (the class), which can represent the relationship between dierent events with
sophistication. However, as such network grow, they can quickly become somewhat opaque
to human examiners they acquire the black box characteristic of neural networks,

1.5 Dependence derivatives on Naive Bayes
In 2004, Harry Zhang of the University of New Brunswick published a paper titled
The Optimality of Naive Bayes, which dramatically improved on existing conditions
for Naive Bayes optimality. Zhang dened the concept of a dependence-derivative
ratio on an example, and showed that, when this ratio is close to 1, the dependence
between attributes is not greatly detrimental to the performance of Naive Bayes. (Zhang
did this using standard and reasonably intuitive denitions for terms like good and
performance, which we will specify later.)
As described, Bayesian classiers determine which class is most likely for a given ex-
ample; the classes are each amorphous multivariate probability distributions, the example
is a tiny spot on each of them, and the classier determines which spot is most likely.
When thinking of dependence-derivatives, however, it is better to visualize the classier
as a generalized see-saw, where the classes are the ends and the example is a weight placed
near the fulcrum. The relative likelihood of each of the attribute values pushes the weight
a little to the left or the right, and in the end the sum of these determines the way the
entire apparatus falls. This metaphor illustrates that even small dierences in the way
algorithms estimate the likelihood of attributes can greatly impact classication, and it
also makes it easy to think of particular values of the examples attributes as pushing the
classiers estimate in the direction of one class or another. If, for a particular example,
all but one attributes contain little distinguishing information (that is, none particularly
moves the weight away from the fulcrum), a single attribute strongly associated with a
class can push the classier a great deal in the direction of that class.
1. INTRODUCTION 21
With this metaphor in mind, consider the dierence between how the naive and full
Bayesian classiers interpret attribute values. To the naive classier, each attribute value
stands alone, and should be evaluated only in its own context; so a value strongly indicating
a particular class will always push the classier in the direction of that class. The full
Bayesian classier is more sophisticated: it also determines if, given the other attribute
values that come in the example, a particular attribute value should be expected to point
in one direction or another simply because of its dependence on the other attributes. A
value strongly indicating a particular class only pushes the full Bayesian classier if it
cannot be explained away by dependence between attributes.
The key observation here is that the full Bayesian classier at most considers attribute
values as having same impact as Naive Bayes does; the impact of an attribute value in the
full classier can never exceed the impact in Naive Bayes. Imagine now how this makes
a dierence when classication is calculated in terms of the see-saw metaphor. Naive
Bayes will see an interesting attribute value and immediately push the weight towards the
class value the attribute indicates. The full Bayesian classier will push the weight, but
then stop, reconsider, and move the weight back towards where it was in proportion to
the extent the attribute value was explained by its dependence on other attributes. The
dependence derivative ratio for an attribute and an example is, essentially, the distance
between the full Bayesian classier and the Naive classier at the end of this process. (In
fact, in Zhangs paper, he denes the ratio arbitrarily and then proves it captures this
idea.) This distance captures the extent to which the dependence between attributes is
aecting Naive Bayes estimate of that attribute value.
The true utility of this idea becomes clear when we think of all the attributes pushing
the classiers, rather than a single one. Each attribute pushes the naive and full Bayesian
classiers, and, each time, the distance between them changes according to the extent
to which that attribute is dependent on the others. But sometimes the distance between
1. INTRODUCTION 22
the classiers is increased, and sometimes it is decreased! In the end, the total eect of
dependence on Naive Bayes is the total distance between the naive and full classiers.
Notice that since the classiers are only sometimes pushed apart, and sometimes pushed
together, that dependence is not always detrimental to Naive Bayes performance. It is
only when dependence of one attribute on others is not balanced out by further dependence
of other attributes in the other direction that Naive Bayes performance degrades. The
global dependence factor, the product of the dependence-derivative ratios for
each attribute of an example, captures the extent to which classication is aected by
dependence.

2.1 Evaluating Classiers
In this section we will dene a series of modications to Naive Bayes, with the aim of using
Zhangs dependence derivatives to improve its performance. Before we do so, however, we
need some terminology with which to evaluate classiers.
Data in the real world is extraordinarily messy, and for this reason it is unrealistic to
expect a classier to accurately predict the class of every object in its training set (let
alone the test set). Therefore, when discussing classiers, we steer clear of terminology that
reects a sense of perfectibility in classier performance. The particular word in question
we have in mind is optimal. Strictly speaking, the optimal classier is the one that
performs best on test data. Because a classier does not encounter the test data until it is,
well, tested, the optimal classier is therefore the one that strikes the best balance between
optimizing performance on the training data and avoiding the problem of over-training,
in which the model implicit in the classier becomes overly tted to the training data
and loses its eectiveness on the test data. Notice, however, that this point of optimal
training varies with the degree to which the training data truly represents the test data. A
2. BETWEEN NAIVE AND FULL BAYES 26
classier that ts itself to the training set closely will perform well on well-represented test
data and badly on badly-represented test data. A classier that does not t the training
data particularly closely will be less aected by a decrease in the quality of the test datas
representation, but will similarly benet less from an increase in the quality of training
data. As a consequence of this fact, it is common when comparing classiers to assume
that the test data and training data are drawn from the same source typically one sets
aside a small portion of the data as for testing, and trains on the rest and that this
partitioning has been randomized and repeated a number of times (a procedure called
folded cross-validation). This is essentially as close to truly representative training data
as can be constructed; however this method of comparison has as a downside that it does
not give a researcher an iron-clad assessment of the optimal classier in other situations.
It is practical enough, however, as in many common uses of classiers, this same method
of folded cross-validation can be used in the eld.
With that extended aside, we will now briey dene some terminology for assessing
classier performance. In the aftermath of a test run, all classiers will produce an error
matrix, which details exactly how many objects of each class were classied as each so
a two-class problem with classes positive and negative will yield entries for false positives
(FP), false negatives (FN), true positives (TP), and true negatives (TN). The error matrix
looks like

1. The classier is performing perfectly if and only if the matrix is diagonal.
2. If the classier decides everything in the test data is in the positive class, the matrix
will only be non-zero in the rst row.

be non-zero in the rst column.
5. If the test case contains only examples from the negative class, the matrix will only
be non-zero in the second column.

of what they represent in terms of the classiers performance. For example, specicity
and sensitivity are counterparts; a classier is said to be sensitive if it correctly classies
most objects in the positive class, while it is specic if it only calls positive those objects
that are in fact positive. An ideal classier would have high values for both sensitivity and
specicity; however, in some situations it is benecial to emphasize one over the other.
Imagine the following scenario: after an industrial accident, a very large number of
people are suddenly at risk for developing an extraordinarily rare, but potentially life-
threatening disease. The presence of the disease can be easily determined with a simple
blood test, but so many people are at risk that it is not possible to test everyone. However,
scientists soon determine that people with certain medical characteristics are much more
likely to develop this disease than others. A binary classier is employed to nd people
whose medical records indicate they might be one of these high-risk patients. In this
situation, the cost of a false positive (declaring someone is high risk when they are not) is
far less than a false negative (declaring someone is low risk when they are not); therefore,
a high-sensitivity classier would be much more useful than a high-specicity or balanced
classier.

2.2 Modifying Naive Bayes algorithm
With the ability to assess classier performance, a sense of how Bayesian classiers t into
the general scheme of statistical estimators, and Zhangs dependence-derivative ratios, we
are nally in a position to propose and evaluate modications of the classic Bayesian clas-
siers. The general idea is to use dependence-derivatives to nd ecient ways of creating
a classier that contains elements of both the naive and full algorithms. By now, it should
be clear that the naive and full classiers are opposite ends of a scale from minimally
tting the data to tting the data as closely as possible. We will create algorithms that
will occupy the interior of this scale. To do that, we rst have to dene a measure of where
on this scale a classier lies.
We see two ways in which we can dene this scale; both involve setting aside a set of
attributes to be treated dierently from others. In the strong version, we assume that
these attributes are independent of the others; in the weaker version, we assume they are
merely unaected by them (and are free to aect the others).
Denition 2.2.1. Let f be a Bayesian classier operating on a dataset with n attributes.
The strong naivete of the classier is the number of attributes that the classier assumes
are independent of the rest.
Denition 2.2.2. Let f be a Bayesian classier operating on a dataset with n attributes.
The weak naivete of the classier is the number of attributes whose vertices in the
digraph of the classier are sources. This is not the number of attributes that are assumed
to be independent of the rest. Our assumption is weaker than that: we allow for there to be
2. BETWEEN NAIVE AND FULL BAYES 33
dependence between our attributes, but impose a condition on the direction the classier
assumes inuence is moving.
The naivete of any classier with n attributes varies from 0 to n. Appropriately, the
Naive Bayesian classier has naivete n, while the full Bayesian net has naivete 0. Notice
that in either extreme case, there is no dierence between the strong and weak versions
of naivete. However, simply stating that a classier has a certain naivete value does not
fully determine it, since we do not know which attributes are naive.
Zhangs dependence derivatives provide a way out of this ambiguity. We are, in eect,
dividing the classiers attributes into one set that is to be treated as in the Naive al-
gorithm, and another than we will treat as in the full network. We know that the Naive
classier works best on attributes with a global dependence factor close to 1. Therefore,
for a k-naive classier, we can select the k attributes for which their dependence factor is
closest to 1.

task. The most obvious way go about it is to evaluate the average dependence derivative
ratio of each attribute, and then nd the subset of attributes for which the product of
these weights is closest to 1. Since in a set with n elements, there are
n

subsets of
size k, the number of subsets to consider can vary wildly with k, and can become quite
large. If we wish to nd the maximally balanced set over all possible k, then we have 2
n
subsets to consider, since our search space is the power set of the n attributes. Since it is
not uncommon to have 30 to 40 attributes in real-world classication problems, this is a
serious problem.
That said, we will not try to nd a more ecient method for nding the maximally
balanced subset of attributes. This is because this computational problem, nding the
subset of attributes for which the product of its elements dependence-derivative ratios is
closet to 1, is equivalent to a classic NP-complete problem, which computer scientists have
been attempting to eciently solve for decades: the subset-sum problem. The subset-sum
problem is stated as follows: given a set S of integers, determine if the elements of any
non-empty subset of S sum to 0.
Theorem 2.2.5. Let A be a set of rational numbers. If an algorithm can determine if a
subset of A multiply to 1, then there is a set of rational numbers B for which that algorithm
can solve the subset-sum problem.
Proof. We need a one-to-one map f : Q Q such that f (1) = 0 and f (ab) = f(a) + f (b).

3.1 Creating k-Naive Classiers
In this section we explain the structure of the implementation of the classiers in this
project. However, because a detailed understanding of the implementation of the programs
is not necessary to understand the results, we will be brief. Final copies of all the code
written for the project are included in the appendix.
The classiers are implemented in an object-oriented framework using numpy, a scientic
computing package for Python. A super-class, Bayes Classier, contains a set of default
methods for initializing a classier, storing the training data and statistics relevant to it
(such as means, variances and covariances), and for performing a few basic calculations
such as evaluating the likelihood of a value in the standard normal distribution.
Three classes inherit from Bayes Classier: NaiveBayes, FullBayes, and KStrongNaive-
Bayes (the last class also implements k-weak Naive Bayes). Each class performs additional
initialization functions, such as calculating an optimal naivete, and provides its own meth-
ods for evaluating an example. The classes also provide support for both standard and
logarithmic calculations of probabilities a few months in, it became clear that logarithmic
3. TESTING K-NAIVE CLASSIFIERS 40
calculations were necessary to avoid machine-precision errors. As we noted in the previous
chapter, Naive Bayes and a full Bayesian network can be created by using k-Naive Bayes
classiers for extreme values of k. We wrote these algorithms their own classes to make
debugging easier.
A fourth class, TestHarness, controls the classiers and runs tests on them. On ini-
tialization, it creates instance of a classier as an instance variable and repeatedly calls
that classiers evaluate function to get data. TestHarness is the user-oriented class of the
project, and can run cross-validated tests, test on a given set of test data, return values for
a classiers sensitivity, specicity, F-score, and so on. All the charts below were created
by a script that repeatedly calls TestHarness called Tester and a script called Data that
generates articial datasets.
3.2 Attribute Balance
In this chapter, we empirically verify the claims we have made about Bayesian classiers,
with an eye towards demonstrating the potential of k-maximally-balanced classiers over
the standard Naive Bayes. Our default strategy for testing a claim will be to create an
articial dataset with an interesting property, such as a high level of covariance among
attributes, and observe the change in classier performance as we vary this property. If
the observed changes in classier performance are consistent with what we would expect
given the discussion of Bayesian classiers in the previous chapter, that will be evidence
that we got things right.
The rst parameter to examine this way is attribute balance. Balance is a blanket term
we use to describe the sum of the weight of all attributes in the training set; because the
weight of an attribute can vary widely across data sets, balance does not denote exactly
the sum of the weight, but rather roughly the direction and magnitude of the total weight.
A balance of 1 indicates that there is a large amount of covariance in the direction of
3. TESTING K-NAIVE CLASSIFIERS 41
the negative class; a balance of 1 indicates a large amount of covariance in the direction
of the positive class. A balance of 0 indicates little covariance in either direction.
Unless otherwise specied, these scatter-plots have between 50 and 100 points per clas-
sier represented. The simulated data contain random elements; to reduce the impact of
random variations, each point on the scatter-plot represents the output of a 10-fold cross-
validated test run on a training set of between 150 and 300 4-attribute examples generated
using the parameter on the X-axis. This means each part of the X-axis corresponds with a
unique set of training data. The Y-axis of the point is usually the F-score of the classier;
the X-axis can vary. For easy comparison, multiple classiers are often trained on the
same data set for a particular point. This means that if, for example, three classiers are
represented on a graph, each X-value should have exactly three points above it (so, if you
moved a vertical line from the left hand of the graph to the right, you would always hit
points three at a time).
Here is an easy example of one of these charts: empirical evidence that Naive Bayes
responds as described to attribute covariance. The chart below shows the performance,
as measured by F-score of a full Bayesian classier (red) and a Naive Bayesian classier
(blue).The X-axis is the balance used to create the data set at that particular point. We
expect Naive Bayes to do well when the absolute value of the balance is low, and perform
badly when it is high. The results are shown below.

This scatter-plot matches our expectations well. Notice that while the full Bayesian net-
work is relatively unaected by changes in the balance, Naive Bayes actually performs
better than full Bayes under near-zero balance conditions. This is expected; when the
data are in balance, Naive Bayes is eectively makes fewer assumptions about the data
than full Bayes.
Note that the actual value of the Y-axis displayed in these charts is mostly irrelevant, as

Some data sets have nice, clearly-dened classes with few outliers to confuse the algo-

3.3 Attribute Weight
We have just presented evidence that the classiers are indeed performing as we expect
with respect to attribute balance. However, most of the claims we made in Chapter 2 used
the much more well-dened idea of weight. Recall from Denition 2.2.3 that the weight of
a set S of k attributes is

Zhangs theorem shows that as the product of the dependence derivatives on an example
moves towards 1, the performance of Naive Bayes on the example strictly improves. Since
weight is the product of the average of dependence derivatives over an entire data set, we
expect to see a performance improve as the weight moves toward 1. However because we
are averaging, we do not expect a strict relationship between weight and performance
rather, on average, the k-Naive classier constructed on the k attributes where weight is
closest to 1 should outperform all other combinations of k attributes.

based on the distance of their independent attributes weight from 1, and grouped them
together: all the classiers with weight closest to 1 are represented below in red, the second
closest to 1 are blue, third closest are cyan, and fourth closest are purple. We expect that
overall, red should tend to have the best performance, followed by blue, cyan, and purple.
We expect this to be true regardless of the balance on the x-axis.
This matches well with our expectations: the average score of the red is clearly higher than

3.4 Data Sparsity
The last question we examine in this chapter concerns the rate at which Bayesian classiers
improve their performance as the amount of data available increases. One of the greatest
strengths of Naive Bayes is that it requires a minimal amount of data to begin performing
relatively well. However, because k-Naive classiers make extensive use of the sample
covariance matrix, which is easily biased and requires lots of data to be reliable, we expect
that they will not share this ability to withstand a dearth of data. The next scatter-plot
is the same 4-attribute balance problem that we saw in Section 3.2, except instead of
changing the balance along the X-axis, we hold balance to a constant -.5 and walk the
number of examples in the training data from 10 to 110. As usual, the 1-naive classier
is in red, 2-naive is in blue, and 3-naive is in cyan. For comparison, we also include the
same plot with full Bayes and Naive Bayes.

The only noticeable pattern is the tendency for the classiers performance to become
less variable as the amount of data increases, but this is expected of virtually any statistic.
We believe that further testing will eventually reveal the extra reliance of k-Naive classiers
on an abundance of data.

bottom = self.logNormProb(example[attribute], attribute, c)
dd = top - bottom
return dd
def ddr(self, example, attribute):

def attributeWeight(self, attribute):
ddrs = [self.ddr(example[0:-1], attribute) for example in self.data]
return sum(ddrs) / self.npoints
def optimalnaivete(self, k, exactlyK = True):
# If exactlyK is on, we only look at combinations of exactly size k.
# If exactlyK is off, we look at combinations of size less than or equal to k.
perms = list(itertools.combinations(range(self.nattributes), k))
if not exactlyK:
for i in range(1,k):
perms.extend(list(itertools.combinations(range(self.nattributes), i)))
bestweightsum = -10000000
for perm in perms:
perm = list(perm)
weightsum = sum([self.weights[attribute] for attribute in perm])
if abs(weightsum) < abs(bestweightsum):
bestperm = perm
bestweightsum = weightsum
return bestperm

# These metrics only make sense in the context of binary classification
def precision(self, errormatrix, classvalue = 0):
return self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, classvalue) /
*BR*(self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, classvalue) +
*BR*self.falsePositiveRate(errormatrix, classvalue))
def recall(self, errormatrix, classvalue = 0):
if classvalue == 0:
return self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0) /
*BR*(self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0) + self.falsePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1))
if classvalue == 1:
return self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1) /
*BR*(self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1) + self.falsePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0))
def fscore(self, errormatrix, classvalue = 0):
return (2 * self.precision(errormatrix, classvalue) * self.recall(
*BR*errormatrix, classvalue)) / (self.precision(errormatrix, classvalue) +
*BR*self.recall(errormatrix, classvalue))
def specificity(self, errormatrix, classvalue = 0):
if classvalue == 0:
return self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1) / (self.
*BR*truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1) + self.falsePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0))
if classvalue == 1:
return self.truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0) / (self.
*BR*truePositiveRate(errormatrix, 0) + self.falsePositiveRate(errormatrix, 1))
